05327nam a22008295i 9780231543255DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979777071  a97802315432557 a10.7312/arse180782doi  a(DE-B1597)480246  a(OCoLC)954038592  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV8599.U6 7aPOL0370002bisacsh04a364.67509732231 aArsenault, Elizabeth Grimm, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow the Gloves Came Off :bLawyers, Policy Makers, and Norms in the Debate on Torture /cElizabeth Grimm Arsenault. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in Terrorism and Irregular Warfare00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. History of Pow Treatment in The United States -- t3. Modern Pow Treatment in The United States -- t4. Pow Treatment and Lawyers -- t5. Pow Treatment and Policy Makers -- t6. Pow Treatment and Interrogators -- t7. Implications and Recommendations -- tAppendix A: Who’s Who -- tAppendix B: Timeline of Major Events -- tAppendix C: Acronyms -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe treatment of detainees at Abu Ghraib prison, Guantánamo Bay, and far-flung CIA "black sites" after the attacks of 9/11 included cruelty that defied legal and normative prohibitions in U.S. and international law. The antitorture stance of the United States was brushed aside. Since then, the guarantee of American civil liberties and due process for POWs and detainees has grown muddled, threatening the norms that sustain modern democracies. How the Gloves Came Off considers the legal and political arguments that led to this standoff between civility and chaos and their significant consequences for the strategic interests and standing of the United States. Unpacking the rhetoric surrounding the push for unitary executive action in wartime, How the Gloves Came Off traces the unmaking of the consensus against torture. It implicates U.S. military commanders, high-level government administrators, lawyers, and policy makers from both parties, exposing the ease with which powerful actors manipulated ambiguities to strip detainees of their humanity. By targeting the language and logic that made torture thinkable, this book shows how future decision makers can craft an effective counternarrative and set a new course for U.S. policy toward POWs and detainees. Whether leaders use their influence to reinforce a prohibition of cruelty to prisoners or continue to undermine long-standing international law will determine whether the United States retains a core component of its founding identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aPrisoners of warzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aTorturexGovernment policyzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2017z978311065472108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2017z9783110548242oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/arse1807840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231543255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231543255.jpg  a978-3-11-054330-8